From 404ba01e505ac13c3446c70673f4d0f69089611e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Mykola Lysenko <mykolal@meta.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 18:05:21 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] um/x86: disable %gs-relative JIT features on UML
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The x86-64 BPF JIT lowers per-cpu addressing (BPF_MOV64_PERCPU_REG,
inlined per-cpu array/hash map lookups, inlined bpf_get_smp_processor_id)
and the private stack pointer to %gs-relative accesses through
this_cpu_off. A UML kernel is a host user process: %gs points at host
TLS, not the guest per-cpu area, so the computed addresses are garbage.
The first store through an inlined per-cpu map value pointer
faults unrecoverably (stores have no probe-mem guard and no BPF
extable entry) and segv() panics the guest: "Kernel tried to access
user memory at addr 0x7f7f928c5000, ip 0xd08a5777", found via gdb on
the get_stack_raw_tp selftest, whose rawdata_map is a
BPF_MAP_TYPE_PERCPU_ARRAY.

Make bpf_jit_supports_percpu_insn() and bpf_jit_supports_private_stack()
return false on UML: the verifier then keeps per-cpu map lookups as
helper calls and skips private-stack setup, both of which go through the
generic (correct) per-cpu accessors.

Signed-off-by: Mykola Lysenko <mykolal@meta.com>
---
 arch/x86/net/bpf_jit_comp.c | 13 +++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/arch/x86/net/bpf_jit_comp.c b/arch/x86/net/bpf_jit_comp.c
index 775fa1a8c..e020155a0 100644
--- a/arch/x86/net/bpf_jit_comp.c
+++ b/arch/x86/net/bpf_jit_comp.c
@@ -4271,7 +4271,15 @@ bool bpf_jit_supports_subprog_tailcalls(void)
 
 bool bpf_jit_supports_percpu_insn(void)
 {
-	return true;
+	/*
+	 * Per-cpu addressing is emitted as %gs-relative accesses to
+	 * this_cpu_off, but a UML kernel is a host user process whose %gs
+	 * base is host TLS, not the guest per-cpu area: the computed
+	 * addresses are garbage and the first store through an inlined
+	 * per-cpu map value pointer faults unrecoverably (stores have no
+	 * probe-mem guard or BPF extable entry). Fall back to helper calls.
+	 */
+	return !IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_UML);
 }
 
 void bpf_jit_free(struct bpf_prog *prog)
@@ -4320,7 +4328,8 @@ bool bpf_jit_supports_exceptions(void)
 
 bool bpf_jit_supports_private_stack(void)
 {
-	return true;
+	/* The private stack pointer is %gs-relative too; see above. */
+	return !IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_UML);
 }
 
 void arch_bpf_stack_walk(bool (*consume_fn)(void *cookie, u64 ip, u64 sp, u64 bp), void *cookie)
-- 
2.43.0

